data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple** return types for `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` casts:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>` — compile-time type safety
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuple syntax instead of array syntax

The test method signature stays the same. MSTest automatically destructures the tuple into the method parameters. If you accidentally add a `(123, true)` row, you'll now get a compiler error instead of a runtime cast failure.
